<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Troops Fire in Air To Disperse Demonstrators </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0501131894 Paris AFP in English 1238 GMT 5 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0501131894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sanaa, Jan 5 (AFP)--Troops fired in the air to 
disperse demonstrators protesting over price rises in the 
southern Yemeni town of Ta'izz, witnesses said Wednesday [5 
January]. 
  There was no report of casualties from Tuesday night's 
clashes, according to the witnesses reached by telephone. 
  Armed police were out in force and shops closed in the 
capital Sanaa on Wednesday during peaceful protests. 
  The demonstrations followed a fall in the value of the riyal 
which has pushed up consumer prices. 
  It was trading at more than 70 to the dollar on the black 
market this week, compared with 60 a week ago. The official is 
rate is 12 to the dollar. 
  The central bank has been unable to prop up the riyal 
because 
of its meagre foreign currency reserves. 
  The economic situation has been exacerbated by a long 
running 
dispute between President 'Ali 'Abdallah Salih, a northerner, 
and his deputy, 'Ali Salim al-Bid, a southerner, over how to run 
the country. 
  Yemen, in the southwest corner of the Arabian peninsula, is 
one of the world's poorest countries, with a per capita income 
of 500 dollars per year. 

</TEXT>

