<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Peres, Rabin React to Taba Talks Resumption </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0601094394 Tel Aviv IDF Radio in Hebrew 0830 GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA0601094394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv IDF Radio </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres says that if the 
Palestinians will want to discuss the editorial and stylistic 
aspects of the Cairo understandings in Taba, Israel will not 
object. As far as the contents are concerned, Peres said the 
Cairo understandings will serve as the basis for the 
continuation of the Taba talks. Minister Peres told our 
political correspondent Udi Segal that the Palestinians have 
learned that Israel is serious when it says it will not 
compromise on security issues and that this is not merely a 
matter of tactics and bargaining. The foreign minister said 
that the contacts between Nabil Sha'th and himself lasted for 
several days because Israel wanted to make it clear to the 
Palestinians that it is acting cautiously and is not pressed for 
time. Our political correspondent notes that Israel wants the 
Taba talks to go on continuously in order to attain quick 
progress. 
  A short time ago, Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin also 
commented 
on the resumption of the Taba talks next week. According to 
Rabin the negotiations, which will be based on the Cairo 
understandings, are aimed at attaining a detailed agreement on 
Gaza and Jericho. This morning, Rabin visited the settlement of 
Na'ama where he met the local residents. Our correspondent in 
the territories Golan Yokhpaz brought this report from the 
Allenby Bridge border crossing: 
  [Begin recording] [Yokhpaz] A short time ago, Prime 
Minister Yitzhaq Rabin, who is visiting this crossing point, 
said that the Taba talks will be based mainly on the 
understandings reached by Israel and the Palestinians in Cairo. 
The prime minister arrived here accompanied by Chief of Staff 
Ehud Baraq and, together with other IDF [Israel Defense Forces] 
officers, they visited the settlement of Na'ama in the Jordan 
Valley. Local settlers have claimed that in the framework of 
the Jericho autonomy plan, their settlement will turn into an 
enclave within the Jericho area. 
  Rabin told the settlers that Israel considers the Jordan 
Valley a security zone because of the area's importance for the 
country's security. This is what Rabin said regarding the 
resumption of the Taba talks next week: 
  [Rabin] In Taba we want to reach a detailed, clear, and 
lucid agreement. In everything relating to Gaza-Jericho First, 
the talks will be based on the Cairo understandings. If they 
backtrack.... [pauses] Everything we said hinges on compliance 
with all the components of the Gaza-Jericho First agreement. 
[end recording] 
  [Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew at 0900 GMT on 6 January 
adds: "Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin says that there is no 
territorial controversy or security problems between Israel and 
Jordan, but Amman is unwilling to be the first party to sign a 
peace treaty with Israel. During his visit to Na'ama and the 
Allenby Bridge, the prime minister also said he is opposed to 
discussing the permanent agreement at this point, not only 
because of our commitment to the Madrid conference but also 
because he is opposed to uprooting settlements and to 
negotiations on the issue of Jerusalem. Our settlement affairs 
correspondent Gil Litman reports that the prime minister told 
Na'ama settlers that he understands their grievances, but Israel 
is interested in solving the conflict with the Palestinians."] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

