<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Beilin: Arab Economic Boycott Becoming `Void' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0501180194 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 1700 GMT 5 Jan 
94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0501180194 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Deputy Foreign Minister Yosi Beilin said the Arab 
economic boycott is becoming void and even the Arab states are 
changing their attitude toward it. Arab businessmen are 
visiting Israel to investigate the possibility of investing 
here. Four Arab states -- Oman, Qatar, Tunisia, and Morocco -- 
have expressed a willingness to host the economic committees in 
the multilateral negotiations. There is a readiness by 
multinational companies, which had previously caved in to the 
boycott, to invest in Israel. Even in Japan -- the largest state 
to support the boycott -- there has been a revolutionary change 
and Japanese businessmen and companies plan to invest in Israel. 
He said, however, that he still finds it hard to foresee an 
Arab League decision to annul the boycott. Our correspondent 
Yo'el Nir reports that Deputy Foreign Minister Beilin made the 
remarks in answer to a motion in the Knesset. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

