<F P=100> JORDAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   PLO's Qaddumi Arrives for Coordination Meetings </TI></H3>
<H4>   Qaddumi Denies `Crisis' in Ties </H4>
<F P=102> JN0501203694 Amman Jordan Television Network in Arabic 1800 
GMT 5 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN0501203694 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman Jordan Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Faruq Qaddumi, head of the PLO Political Department, 
made the following statement to our correspondent upon his 
arrival in Amman this morning: 
  [Begin recording] [Qaddumi] First comes coordination. We are 
one people and one country. In fact, coordination and 
cooperation are a must. We should explore the future and how 
the situation will be in the Middle East. The Jordanians and 
the Palestinians are one people and have common interests. The 
aim is to organize these common interests in the future, to draw 
up rules for them, and to reinforce the brotherly ties between 
us. The previous experiences we have faced as one unit cannot 
be seen as just a relationship between one country and another, 
but as one among the members of one family. This is our concept 
of the work for which we have come and for the future we want to 
work out together, God willing. 
  [Reporter] There is a crisis in Jordanian-Palestinian 
relations. What are the dimensions of this crisis? 
  [Qaddumi] There is no crisis. This is, regrettably, the 
creation of Arab or non-Arab media. There is, in fact, a 
persisting desire to carry out joint action because we are 
moving toward a serious stage. This esplains his majesty's 
statement that stressed desire to base relations on sound 
foundations. This, in fact, is our opinion and our trend. 
Therefore, what is being portrayed as a crisis is not a crisis 
at all. There is not crisis among the members of one family. 
[end recording] 

</TEXT>

