<F P=100> JORDAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   PLO's Qaddumi Arrives for Coordination Meetings </TI></H3>
<H4>   Al-'Anani Views Talks </H4>
<F P=102> JN0501205294 Amman Jordan Television Network in English 2000 
GMT 5 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN0501205294 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman Jordan Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "News at Ten" program] </F>
  [Text] The Jordanian and the Palestinian officials held 
another round of talks this evening. Minister of Information 
Dr. Jawad al-'Anani said the talks were open and candid, but 
that tangible results have yet to be achieved. 
  [Begin recording] [Al-'Anani] Well, I think that the 
meetings 
were very open, very candid. They dealt with down-to-earth 
issues. It was very much businesslike. We have agreed that we 
agree on the basic principles and the guiding aims for our 
internal dialogue. However, we feel that this is necessary but 
not sufficient. What is sufficient is to arrive at tangible and 
practical steps that people can feel, make a difference of their 
own lives. And we assure them that the process of negotiations 
is going to ensure their own concerns. 
  [Reporter] Dr. al-'Anani: Do you think that the king's last 
speech has put a lot more pressure on the PLO to deal with the 
issues that are still in the air with the Palestinians and 
Jordanians? 
  [Al-'Anani] I do not need to analyze his majesty's motives. 
I think that the speech of his majesty was very clear, very 
candid. He was showing a great deal of concern that we need more 
coordination, and this coordination is not only a Jordanian 
demand, but it is a Jordanian as well as a Palestinian demand. 
  [Reporter] When do you expect the signing? 
  [Al-'Anani] We expect that we should continue to negotiate. 
[end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

