<F P=100> Pakistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister Briefs Assembly Committee on Kashmir </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0501142494 Islamabad PTV Television Network in English 
1400 GMT 5 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0501142494 </F>
<F P=104>  Islamabad PTV Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The special committee of the National Assembly on 
Kashmir was informed today that Pakistan's principled stand on 
the Kashmir issue was put across to the Indian side during the 
Pak-India talks. The foreign minister, Sardar Asif Ahmad Ali, 
while briefing the committee on Pak-India talks in Islamabad 
today, said that the talks focused on the Kashmir issue. The 
Pakistan side emphasized that India must take visible steps to 
reduce repression in the Indian-held Kashmir, including 
deinduction [reduction] of troops from the valley, release of 
political leaders, and their unhindered access to the human 
rights organizations and foreign governments. The committee was 
informed by the foreign minister that although the talks failed 
to achieve any results, the fact that Kashmir remained the focus 
of attention during the talks and acknowledgment by India that 
Kashmir was a disputed area amounts to a diplomatic gain for us. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

