<F P=100> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Disappearance of Libyan Dissident </TI></H3>
<H4>   Interior Ministry Forms Search Teams </H4>
<F P=102> NC0601075194 Cairo AL-'ARABI in Arabic 3 Jan 94 pp 1, 7 </F>
<F P=103> NC0601075194 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo AL-'ARABI </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Egyptian Interior Ministry briefed the Arab 
Human Rights Organization [AHRO) on the results of the searches 
for and investigations into the disappearance of former Libyan 
Foreign Minister Mansur al-Kikhya, who was reported missing more 
than three weeks ago. 
  After meeting with Interior Minister Hasan al-Alfi 
yesterday, 
AHRO Secretary General Muhammad Fa'iq said that the Interior 
Ministry has formed 10 search teams to find decisive information 
about al-Kikhya's whereabouts. The Investigations are 
continuing. Fa'iq said that he believed the Egyptian security 
authorities are showing real concern about al-Kikhya's 
whereabouts. Fa'iq said the Interior Minister told him that 
President Mubarak is personally interested in this issue and 
that Mubarak is regularly updated on the progress of the 
investigations. 
  Fa'iq will leave for Beirut in two days to attend the 
extraordinary meeting of the AHRO Executive Committee on 7 
January. The Executive Committee will discuss the details of 
al-Kikhya's disappearance, unravel the ambiguity surrounding his 
fate, and define the steps that should be taken to secure his 
safety. Fa'iq said the AHRO will discuss the formation of a 
higher national committee to secure the safety of al-Kikhya and 
the safety of political refugees in general. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

