<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   'Abd-Rabbuh on Coordination Problems With Jordan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  JN0501174394 Amman AKHIR KHABAR in Arabic 4-5 Jan 94 p 22 </F>
<F P=103> JN0501174394 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman AKHIR KHABAR </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Fathi al-Barqawi] </F>
  [Excerpt] Tunisia -- Three topics were on the agenda of the 
PLO Executive Committee meetings over the past two days. These 
issues are: Relations with Jordan; the stumbling negotiations 
with the Israelis; and the internal Palestinian course. Yasir 
'Abd-Rabbuh, member of the PLO Executive Committee, spoke to 
AKHIR KHABAR following the meetings, which ended Monday [3 
January] afternoon. 
  Regarding relations with Jordan, 'Abd-Rabbuh said: The 
Jordanian and Palestinian sides agreed, during the meeting 
between His Majesty King Husayn and Palestinian President Yasir 
'Arafat on Thursday, to activate the joint coordination 
committees and to instruct these committees to be practical in 
their deliberations and to directly deal with the major issues 
that must be viewed as priorities. He added: Despite the delay 
in the work of the committees, we believe that it is not too 
late and that there is a possibility for avoiding such a 
shortcoming. 
  'Abd-Rabbuh said: It is obvious that the problem on our part 
does not lie in our hesitation in or refrain from reaching the 
highest level of coordination, but in the lack of progress in 
the talks to end the Israeli occupation of even a part of the 
Palestinian territory. Any agreement with sisterly Jordan will 
be useless and cannot be practically applied without ending the 
occupation. We reached an understanding with our brothers in 
Jordan that discussing future relations, particularly on the 
political level, depends on the establishment of a Palestinian 
entity on Palestinian land and on ending the Israeli occupation. 
He said: The relationship should be established between two 
independent entities on an equal footing. He added that the 
same thing applies to the economic and security issues. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

