<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Israeli Press Report on Negotiations With PLO </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0501123094 FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>
<F P=103> TA0501123094 </F>
<F P=104>  FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>



<TEXT>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] Most Israeli dailies on 5 January offer 
extensive coverage of the Israeli negotiations with the PLO. 
They report that progress has been made and two sides are 
coming closer together, allowing for the probable resumption of 
the Taba talks by next week. 
  Jerusalem THE JERUSALEM POST in English, in a page 1 report 
compiled by Alon Pinkas, Batsheva Tsur, and news agencies, 
writes that "Senior sources in Jerusalem said progress has been 
made on several points, which were contained in the fax sent to 
the PLO." The POST details some of the controversial points. 
Concerning control of the Jordan River bridges the report 
states: "the compromise will allow for a symbolic Palestinian 
presence." On the issue of international supervisors at the 
checkpoints, "the PLO will accept Israel's refusal to allow any 
international force or observers to be present." Regarding 
Palestinian access to the Dead Sea the sides will agree that 
"the issue be further negotiated." On the issue of private 
land, the POST writes that "the IDF [Israel Defense Forces] -- 
in the areas which it controls -- will respect privately owned 
Palestinian land." 
  Tel Aviv HA'ARETZ in Hebrew, in a page A1 report by Aluf 
Ben, 
Gay Bekhor, 'Aqiva Eldar, and Gid'on Alon, reports on 
yesterday's fax and phone contacts between Foreign Minister 
Shim'on Peres and Nabil Sha'th, in which two issues were 
discussed: "How to define the Cairo understanding, and whether 
this understanding stands on its own or should be seen as part 
in a series of contacts. Israel has expressed willingness to 
soften its definitions and no longer demands to define the Cairo 
draft as an 'agreement'. 
  "According to political sources, the Palestinians are no 
longer referring to PLO Chairman 'Arafat's demands for 
introducing substantial changes into the Cairo understandings. 
This is construed as a concession to the Israeli position." 
  Tel Aviv 'AL HAMISHMAR in Hebrew, in a page 1 report by 
Avner 
Regev, reports that "last week PLO Chairman Yasir 'Arafat phoned 
Knesset Member [MK] 'Abd-al-Wahhab Darawshah and asked him to 
tell Prime Minister Rabin that the Cairo talks entanglement can 
be solved if Rabin agrees to enlarge the Jericho area. In 
exchange 'Arafat will give Israel what it wants on the Jordan 
bridges." The paper goes on to say that Darawshah relayed this 
message to the prime minister. 
  Tel Aviv YEDI'OT AHARONOT in Hebrew, in a report on pages 1 
and 15 by Shim'on Schiffer and Nahum Barne'a, states that 
despite progress, "Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin rejected an 
offer by PLO Chairman Yasir 'Arafat to meet on 15 January, a day 
prior to the Clinton-al-Asad summit in Geneva." 
  Senior political sources, who commented on this issue 
yesterday, said that "'Arafat requested a meeting with Rabin on 
15 January to reach an understanding on the implementation of 
the self-administration in Gaza and Jericho prior to the 
Clinton-al-Asad summit in Geneva on 16 January. According to 
many assessments, the Clinton-al-Asad summit could place the 
Syrian talks at the center of the political negotiations at the 
expense of the Palestinian track. 
  "It has further been learned that Rabin also rejected 
'Arafat's suggestion that they join Clinton and al-Asad at the 
Geneva summit." 
  The report adds that "the prime minister asked the MK's and 
ministers who plan to meet 'Arafat in Tunis to stop these 
private initiatives which harm the negotiations between Israel 
and the PLO'." 
  YEDI'OT also writes that "Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin 
yesterday reiterated his opposition to U.S. mediation in the 
current controversy between Israel and the PLO." Rabin, in a 
farewell party to outgoing U.S. Ambassador Bill Brown, said: 
"We cooked this dish together with the Palestinians, so now we 
will fix it without outside intervention." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

