<H3> <TI>   Report on U.S. Demarche on Jerusalem Plans </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA2912110993 Tel Aviv MA'ARIV in Hebrew 29 Dec 93 p 6--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> TA2912110993 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv MA'ARIV </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Hemi Shalev] </F>
  [Text] The United States has submitted a diplomatic 
demarche to Israel over the government's construction plans in 
"Greater Jerusalem" and over the intention to integrate Ma'ale 
Adumim with the capital. 
  The demarche, which is very unusual in light of the good 
relations currently prevailing between the Clinton 
administration and the Israeli Government, was submitted by U.S. 
Ambassador William Brown to Eytan Bentzur, the deputy director 
general of the Foreign Ministry. 
  The protest came after U.S. officials were amazed by a map 
given to Samuel Lewis, head of policy planning at the State 
Department, by Construction and Housing Minister Binyamin 
Ben-Eli'ezer several weeks ago. On the map, a circle was drawn 
around Jerusalem that greatly exceeded the city's municipal area 
in size. The map also pictured plans for construction between 
Ma'ale Adumim and Jerusalem, Ma'ale Adumim and Giv'at Ze'ev, and 
also between Giv'at Ze'ev and Jerusalem. 
  In reaction to the demarche submitted by Amb. Brown, 
government sources yesterday promised to look into the matter 
and convey a response to the U.S. Government. 

</TEXT>

