<F P=101> Israel </F>
<H3> <TI>   Jewish Neighborhood in East Jerusalem Approved </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0401095394 Jerusalem THE JERUSALEM POST in English 4 Jan 
94 p 3--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> TA0401095394 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem THE JERUSALEM POST </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Bill Hutman] </F>
  [Text] The Jerusalem municipal planning committee 
yesterday approved the first stage in the construction of a 
Jewish housing project near the Bet Orot Yeshiva on the Mount of 
Olives. 
  The committee voted 7-3 to allow Bet Orot to place a dozen 
mobile homes on land adjoining the yeshiva, in the Arab 
neighborhood of al-Tur. 
  The decision came after Mayor Ehud Olmert voiced his support 
for the controversial project. 
  Deputy Mayor Shmu'el Me'ir (NRP) [National Religious Party] 
said approval of the project reflects the new city council's 
plans to increase the Jewish presence in eastern Jerusalem, 
committee sources said. 
  Me'ir said the mobile homes would be followed by 
conventional 
housing, a position also voiced by Bet Orot officials in the 
past. 
  Approval was given against the recommendations of the city's 
planning department, which argued the land was earmarked for an 
Arab school. In an opinion presented to the committee before 
the vote, the department maintained the lot had to be rezoned 
for the plan to be approved, committee sources said. 
  Committee head Uri Lupoliansky presented a letter stating 
the 
department promised to find another site for the Arab school, 
signed by Jerusalem education department head Nisim Solomon. 
  But the planning department said no reasonable alternative 
site exists for the Arab school. 
  Me'ir insisted he knows of four alternatives sites, but 
declined to give their locations, sparking sharp criticism from 
Councilor Yisra'el Shulderman (One Jerusalem). 
  Despite heated exchanges, the plan was easily passed by the 
municipal coalition, joined by My Jerusalem's Yehoram Ga'on. 
The one Meretz and two One Jerusalem members voted against the 
plan. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

