<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Israel </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poll on Golan Pullout, Labor Support </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0301113594 Tel Aviv MA'ARIV in Hebrew 3 Jan 94 p 4--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> TA0301113594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv MA'ARIV </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Hemi Shalev] </F>
  [Text] About half the public believes Israel should use 
only limited force or even abstain from using force to put down 
riots in the territories, according to a poll published this 
week by Bar-Ilan University's Institute for Strategic Studies. 
  About one-third of the public does not know whether to 
support or oppose the agreement between Israel and the PLO, 
while one-half does not believe the agreement will lead to 
comprehensive peace with the Arab countries. According to the 
poll commissioned last month from Modi'in Ezrahi, 60 percent of 
the public support negotiations with the PLO, which represents 
only a 46-percent rise since last March. 
  The poll further shows that 78 percent are either opposed to 
any withdrawal or agree to a very limited withdrawal from the 
Golan Heights. On the other hand, 16 percent support a partial 
withdrawal, and only 4 percent advocate a full withdrawal. 
  As for voting trends, the poll points to a drop in support 
for Labor and Meretz and a surge in the strength of Likud and 
Tzomet. Labor would attain 26 percent of the vote if elections 
were held today (compared with 35 percent in the last election), 
Likud would rise from 25 to 30 percent, Meretz would drop from 
9.5 to 5.6 percent, and Tzomet would rise from 6.35 to 9.78 
percent. 
  As for the agreement with the PLO, the poll shows that 14 
percent support it very much, 21.6 percent support it, 11 
percent oppose it, and 26 percent oppose it very much. Some 27 
percent said they both support and oppose the agreement. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-52676 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes004__a94016" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-004-A </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  6 January 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Israel </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sharon Demands New Likud Primaries </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0501111094 Jerusalem THE JERUSALEM POST in English 5 Jan 
94 p 2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> TA0501111094 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem THE JERUSALEM POST </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Sarah Honig] </F>
  [Text] Likud MK [Knesset member] Ari'el Sharon escalated 
his ongoing campaign against party leader Binyamin Netanyahu 
yesterday, demanding that a new round of primaries be held prior 
to the next general elections. 
  Netanyahu was elected party chairman and candidate for prime 
minister when he won the Likud primary by a landslide last March. 
  Sharon withdrew from the race, but it was clear that he had 
not relinquished his ambitions for leadership and was only 
postponing his challenge. 
  The Likud rules make a new primary impossible without a 75 
percent majority. Sharon suggested this rule be amended. 
  He further argued that the primary result is "not valid or 
relevant any more because it was held at a very difficult time 
for the Likud. By the time new elections are scheduled, things 
will be even more different, hence the need to re-consider who 
is to lead the party to the polls." 
  Taking Netanyahu's leadership to task, Sharon charged that 
"the Likud is not prepared to wage any struggle and it has yet 
to even crystallize its own policies and alternatives. The 
Likud simply does not appear now as the leader of the 
opposition." 
  The remedy for this, according do Sharon, is that rather 
than 
entrust the leadership to Netanyahu, "the Likud be lead by a 
team." 

</TEXT>

