<F P=100> ARAB AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Algeria </F>
<H3> <TI>   Suspect Behind Killing of 12 Croats Identified </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0601142594 Paris AFP in English 1309 GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0601142594 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Algiers, Jan 6 (AFP)--Algerian security officials 
have identified the man behind last month's massacre of 12 
Croats at Tamezguida south of the Algerian capital as Sayeh 
Attia, the EL WATAN daily reported Thursday [6 January]. 
  Security forces have arrested Attia's father-in-law, named 
only as Bouchakor in the report, charging him with sheltering 
the armed gang after the December 15 killings, and have 
recovered stolen goods. 
  Attia was reported to have led an armed band for more than a 
year and to be responsible for more than 200 attacks. He has 
been implicated in an assault on the Boughezoul barracks, 150 
kilometres (90 miles) south of here, which left 19 soldiers 
dead, EL WATAN said. 
  The 12 Croatian expatriate workers, employed by the Croatian 
company Hydro-Elektra, had their throats cut by a gang of about 
30 people, near the dam they were helping build 50 kilometres 
(30 miles) south of Algiers. 
  Last year, foreigners accused of cooperating with the 
Algerian government became the target of Moslem extremists 
waging war against the regime since the cancellation in January 
1992 of elections the now outlawed Islamic Salvation Front was 
poised to win. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

