<F P=100> Libya </F>
<H3> <TI>   Deal Said Struck To Pay Russia To Use UN Veto </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0501182994 Cairo ROSE AL-YUSUF in Arabic 3 Jan 94 p 13 </F>
<F P=103> NC0501182994 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo ROSE AL-YUSUF </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Wa'il al-Ibrashi] </F>
  [Text] Libyan diplomatic sources have revealed that the 
fugitive Egyptian millionaire Tawfiq 'Abd-al-Hayy, who lives in 
Greece, was the main middleman in an abortive deal between Libya 
and Russia before the recent UN Security Council resolution was 
issued. 
  The sources said Tawfiq 'Abd-al-Hayy maintained close 
relations with the Russian ambassador in Greece and introduced 
him to Libyan officials. Libya was to pay Russia $1.8 billion 
immediately in return for Russia using its veto when the draft 
resolution to impose new sanctions against Libya came up for 
voting at the UN Security Council. The deal failed because 
Russia wanted the money paid before it used the veto. Libya 
suspected that Russia would take the money and consider it part 
repayment for Libyan debts to Russia and would not use the veto. 
Libya transferred just $65 million and the deal failed. 
  It is known that the fugitive millionaire, who is wanted in 
Egypt, maintains close relations with 'Abdallah al-Sanusi, a 
close aide to al-Qadhdhafi and the man responsible for his 
security. 
  ROSE AL-YUSUF has learned that the Libyan Council of 
Ministers recently submitted to Mu'ammar al-Qadhdhafi a 
memorandum demanding an investigation into all the funds paid to 
middlemen to solve the Lockerbie crisis without result. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

