<F P=100> Morocco </F>
<H3> <TI>   Marrakech To Host GATT Signing Ceremony </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0601224194 Rabat RTM Television Network in Arabic 2030 GMT 
6 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0601224194 </F>
<F P=104>  Rabat RTM Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] A meeting was held today to discuss the various 
aspects of the final agreement reached on the Uruguay talks. 
  The meeting was chaired by Mr. Mourad Cherif, minister of 
foreign trade, foreign investments, and handicrafts. [passage 
omitted] 
  After the meeting, Mr. Mourad Cherif, minister of foreign 
trade, foreign investments, and handicrafts, made the following 
statement: 
  [Begin Cherif recording] Since 1986, the member states of 
GATT have been holding the Uruguay talks. These negotiations 
ended on 15 December last year with an agreement which will be 
signed on 15 April this year. 
  It honors me to announce that the choice of the 
participating 
parties has fallen on the city of Marrakech to host the trade 
ministers' meeting during April this year. That was in response 
to a proposal by His Majesty King Hassan II, may God make him 
victorious. The final agreement of the Uruguay rounds will be 
signed during this meeting and the birth of the General 
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade will be announced. 
  This choice is proof of confidence in and excellence of our 
country on the international sphere, and puts the seal on our 
encouraging and recorded economic achievements during a decade 
of structural reform. [passage omitted] 
  The success of the Uruguay rounds, God willing, will add 
(?100) billion dollars to world revenue until the year 2000, 
according to a study carried out by the World Bank and the 
Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development. 
  The reduction in tariffs which the participating parties 
will 
give will enable Moroccan goods to enter foreign markets. The 
signing of the agreement in the city of Marrakech will give 
positive and important results to the Moroccan economy in 
general and our exports in particular. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

