<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Palestinian Group-PLO Talks Conclude in Tunis </TI></H3>
<H4>   Reassurance Sought on Reform Demands </H4>
<F P=102> PM0601122494 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 5 Jan 94 p4 </F>
<F P=103> PM0601122494 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ['Ali al-Salih report: "Dr. 'Abd-al-Shafi Tells AL-SHARQ </F>
AL-AWSAT: Before Leaving Tunis We Would Like To Feel Somewhat 
Reassured About Our Demands"] 
  [Text] London -- Dr. Haydar 'Abd-al-Shafi, who is heading a 
delegation representing the signatories of what is now known as 
the reform memorandum submitted to the PLO Executive Committee 
last month, has stated: "Before leaving Tunis, we would like to 
feel somewhat reassured that our demands will be met." 
  He added that "the purpose of the current meetings is to 
work 
for the implementation of what the signatories spelled out in 
their memorandum, particularly exercise of democracy in the 
management of PLO affairs and the employment of qualified 
Palestinians, irrespective of political and personal factors." 
Dr. 'Abd-al-Shafi, who was speaking to AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT by 
telephone from Tunis, described the meetings already held as 
good, with no fundamental differences and no emotionalism. The 
purpose of these meetings, he said, was to exchange views. 
  He said that last night's session was devoted to a 
discussion 
of the brief memorandum submitted to the Executive Committee 
during the meeting. 
  It should be noted that, in addition to Dr. Haydar 
'Abd-al-Shafi, the reform delegation includes 'Abd-al-Hafiz 
al-Ashhab (independent), Taysir 'Aruri (People's Party), Nabil 
'Amr (member of Fatah's Revolutionary Council), Ibrahim 
Abu-'Abbas (former engineers' doyen in Jordan), Tawfiq Abu-Bakr 
(independent journalist), and Ghazi al-Khalili (Fida Party). 
  Dr. 'Abd-al-Shafi refused to say what the memorandum was 
about but said that it was derived from "the main document." 
Asked if the brief memorandum included practical steps for the 
implementation of their demands, Dr. 'Abd-al-Shafi said: "Let 
us not anticipate events." 
  Commenting on the statement attributed to him that he would 
not leave Tunis "empty-handed," Dr. 'Abd-al-Shafi said: "We did 
not come to Tunis just to look at one another. Our people are 
facing major challenges and the necessary measures must be taken 
to meet these challenges." 
  In reply to the question what do you hope to achieve, he 
said: "That our viewpoint should be upheld in principle. Before 
leaving Tunis we would like to feel somewhat reassured that our 
demands will be met or that they are on the way to being met." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-52705 </DOCNO>
