<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Opposition Parties Withdraw From Talks Committee </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM0601115494 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 5 Jan 94 pp 
1, 4 </F>

<F P=103> PM0601115494 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Lutfi Shatarah report: "Withdrawal of Yemeni Opposition </F>
From Dialogue Committee"] 
  [Excerpt] Aden -- All parties taking part in the Political 
Dialogue Committee have withdrawn from the committee with the 
exception of the representatives of the ruling tripartite 
coalition (the Yemeni Socialist Party, the General People's 
Congress, and the Reform Grouping). 
  The Dialogue Committee had come a long way when it resumed 
its meetings in Aden last Sunday but representatives of the 
opposition parties felt that there was what they called 
"procrastination, dithering, and time-wasting" by the Yemeni 
Socialist Party and the General People's Congress at the 
meetings held the day before yesterday. 
  The withdrawn parties include the opposition's National Bloc 
parties, Deputy Prime Minister Brigadier General Mujahid 
Abu-Shawarib, the Patriotic Forces Union, the Ba'th Party, 
representatives of the "Yemeni Revolution's Fighters," and the 
September Party representative Brigadier General Ahmad Qarhash. 
These parties decided to hold a meeting this evening to take a 
clear and decisive stance on the issues under discussion and on 
the dialogue itself. 
  Some partisan sources have accused some members of the 
coalition, whom they declined to name, of using the time factor 
to foil the dialogue and carry out previous designs. 
  The sources told AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT that the withdrawing 
parties and figures would announce a resolution to the effect 
that "there should either be a dialogue aimed at achieving good 
and tangible results or no dialogue at all, in which case the 
coalition parties obstructing the dialogue will be held fully 
responsible." [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

