<F P=100> JORDAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Coordination Talks With PLO Continue in Amman </TI></H3>
<H4>   `Frustration' Reportedly Prevails </H4>
<F P=102> JN0601130594 Paris Radio Monte Carlo in Arabic 1200 GMT 6 
Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN0601130594 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris Radio Monte Carlo </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Randah Habib dispatch from Amman] </F>
  [Text] At a time when the Jordanian-Palestinian talks are 
being held in Amman for the second consecutive day to launch a 
serious dialogue between the two sides, an atmosphere of 
frustration has prevailed these talks, and it seems they will 
not produce any positive results. King Husayn had earlier 
stressed that these talks will be the last opportunity to 
rectify the situation following the PLO's continuous 
procrastination. 
  Observers believe that Palestinian President Yasir 'Arafat's 
decision to send Faruq Qaddumi to Amman, taking into 
consideration that the latter is not informed of the 
coordination file, unlike Mahmud 'Abbas, Abu-Mazin, reflects 
'Arafat's desire to procrastinate and gain time, especially 
since the Palestinian delegation is expected to ask for time to 
hold consultations with the leadership in Tunis, something which 
will lead to revolving in the same vicious circle. 
  An authorized Jordanian source has stressed that Jordan has 
the feeling that 'Arafat gives priority to coordination with 
Israel at the expense of coordination with Jordan. The source 
noted that Amman does not want to get involved in the whirlpool 
of turning the conflict from a Palestinian-Israeli conflict into 
a Palestinian-Jordanian conflict. However, the source added, 
Amman holds the PLO responsible for the repercussions of the 
failure of the dialogue in Amman, and the additional suffering 
this would cause to the Palestinian people inside the occupied 
territories. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

