<F P=100> Iran </F>
<H3> <TI>   Velayati on Niyazov Visit, Afghanistan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0601155794 Tehran IRIB Television Second Program Network 
in English 1430 GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0601155794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRIB Television Second Program Network 
in English 1430 GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Exclusive" Interview with Foreign Minister 'Ali Akbar </F>
Velayati by unidentified correspondent; place and date not 
given--recorded] 
  [Text] [Correspondent] Mr. Foreign Minister, what were the 
main issues discussed between the visiting Turkmen delegation 
and the Iranian officials. 
  [Velayati] In the name of God, the merciful, the 
compassionate. His Excellency President Saparmurad Niyazov has 
come here on the basis of the invitation of our president, and 
he has reciprocated the recent visit of our president to 
Turkmenistan. He and his entourage stayed here for five days. 
During their stay here they have made very good discussions 
with their Iranian counterparts in different ministries and in 
different committees. At the end of his trip we had signed 
eleven documents. Three of these documents were signed by [the] 
two presidents. I think after the signing of these documents 
many facilities have been provided for the expansioning of 
relations between our two countries. 
  [Correspondent] As you know, Afghanistan is now facing a 
very critical situation. What are the measures and stances 
taken by Iran towards the on-going Afghan crisis? 
  [Velayati] This is [a] very unfortunate situation. You know 
the people of Afghanistan since the very beginning after the 
occupation of that country by the former Soviet forces, they 
have tried a lot to expel the former Soviet forces and they have 
succeeded. So the first part of their struggle was very 
successful. But, unfortunately, after the victory of the Islamic 
revolution in Afghanistan they have started fighting against 
each other. We as the Islamic Republic of Iran are against any 
kind of internal conflict. We don't support any party against 
another party. What we have done till now is bringing all 
factions together and trying to make a peaceful settlement among 
all these factions which are fighting against each other. We 
deeply believe that any kind of internal conflict is against the 
interest of the people of Afghanistan. 
  [Reporter] Iran has decided to resume diplomatic relations 
with South Africa. On what basis has this decision been made 
and how long the normalization of ties will continue? 
  [Velayati] You know this decision was made last night in the 
Cabinet meeting, and we have been instructed by the government 
to prepare the ground for resumption of relations with South 
Africa. After the recent important developments we could witness 
in South Africa and on the basis of the request of the head of 
important groups there, ANC [African National Congress] and EAC 
[Ease African Community], and specifically Mr. Mandela has asked 
us to resume our relations, and Muslim groups in South Africa 
also have asked us. So we think that as a first step we have to 
resume our economic relations with South Africa, and after the 
elections, which will be held in, before the end of April, after 
the end of that elections we think that the time will be right 
for the resumption of the political relations. 
  [Reporter] Thank you very much, sir. 
  [Velayati] You are welcome. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-52756 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes005_s_94012" </HT>


