<F P=100> Sri Lanka </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tamil Rebels Suspected of Killing Politician </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0501140594 Hong Kong AFP in English 1108 GMT 5 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> BK0501140594 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Colombo, Jan 5 (AFP) - Suspected Tamil rebels killed 
a prospective candidate ahead of elections to local government 
bodies in Sri Lanka's embattled northeast, and warned others 
against participating, officials said Wednesday. 
  Gunmen believed to be from the separatist Liberation Tigers 
of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) dragged out Kanagaratnam Jeevaratnam from 
his home in eastern Sittandy late Tuesday, shot him dead and 
dumped his body in the town, officials said. 
  "There was also a note by the side (of the body) warning 
that 
others who try to contest will also get the same treatment," a 
local official in the east said, adding it was "definitely" the 
work of the LTTE. 
  Jeevaratnam was planning to stand as an independent 
candidate 
in the local government elections due to be held shortly. 
However, exact dates of balloting have not yet been announced. 
  Nominations for the local government polls were being 
received from Wednesday in the eastern districts of Trincomalee, 
Batticaloa and Ampara and northern Vavuniya. Nominations close 
on January 12. 
  The LTTE has called on Tamil parties to boycott the polls 
and 
had put up posters in the east, threatening those who 
participated in the polls with death. 
  Since the parliamentary elections of February 1989, there 
has 
been no balloting in the northeast due to the ongoing war 
between government troops and LTTE guerrillas. 
  The LTTE is fighting for a separate state in the northeast 
for Sri Lanka's two million minority Tamils who are concentrated 
in the region. Thousands have died in the LTTE-led independence 
campaign. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

