<H3> <TI>   Minister Departs for Central Asian Republics </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0701092694 Islamabad Radio Pakistan Overseas Service in 
English 0800 GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0701092694 </F>
<F P=104>  Islamabad Radio Pakistan Overseas Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The foreign minister, Sardar Asif Ahmad Ali, left 
Islamabad this morning for an official visit to Central Asian 
states. The week-long tour will take him to Uzbekistan, 
Turkmenistan, and Kazakhstan. Talking to newsmen before his 
departure, he said Pakistan would offer Central Asian republics 
to open up their embassies in Islamabad to help boost bilateral 
cooperation. Pakistan has already concluded about 38 agreements 
with these states for strengthening cooperation in a number of 
fields. He said no progress could be made on the agreements due 
to lack of follow up, and during his current visit he would try 
to remove blockages and revitalize them. Special attention 
would be paid to matters relating to trade, transport, and 
communications. He said Pakistan and China have agreed to sign 
an agreement to make Karakoram Highway a viable road and there 
is a plan to open it up for Kazakhstan and Kyrgyzstan in future. 

