<H3> <TI>   Government Not To Indulge in `Victimization' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0601092894 Islamabad Radio Pakistan Overseas Service in 
English 0800 GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0601092894 </F>
<F P=104>  Islamabad Radio Pakistan Overseas Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Senate today resumed discussion on the 
president's address to the joint session of the Parliament. Mr. 
Abdur Rahim Mandokhel, who was the first speaker today, proposed 
reforms in the Constitution to give it true federal, 
parliamentary, and democratic orientation. He said the affairs 
of the government should be conducted through mutual 
accommodation and understanding between the government and the 
opposition on the one hand, and the center and the provinces on 
the other. The debate is still continuing. 
  Responding to a point of order, the minister for law and 
parliamentary affairs, Syed Iqbal Haider, reiterated the 
government's determination not to indulge in any sort of 
victimization of its political opponents. The point of order 
was raised by Ejazul Islam Jatoi in the Senate this morning, who 
complained that political opponents were being victimized in 
Sindh. Syed Iqbal Haider, however, made it clear that the law 
will take its own course against criminals, terrorists, and 
plunderers of the people's money. 

