<F P=100> India </F>
<H3> <TI>   Report Recommends Opening Insurance Sector </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0701160094 Delhi All India Radio Network in English 1530 
GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0701160094 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi All India Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Malhotra Committee on reforms in the insurance 
sector submitted its report to the finance minister, Dr. 
Manmohan Singh, in New Delhi today. The committee in its report 
has called for allowing the private sector and foreign companies 
in the insurance sector. But it has suggested certain controls 
for its efficient working in the new economic conditions. The 
33-point recommendation submitted by the former governor of the 
Reserve Bank of India, Mr. R.N. Malhotra, has suggested that the 
private sector companies must have a minimum pay-back capital of 
100 crore rupees and the promoter stage should not exceed 40 
percent of the capital. The report said that if the foreign 
insurance companies were allowed, they should float Indian 
companies. The committee has recommended that LIC [Life 
Insurance Corporation] should be converted into a company 
registered under the Companies Act. 
  The report says Postal Life Insurance should be permitted to 
transact life insurance business in the rural areas among the 
general public. The committee has recommended that the 
ownership pattern of the LIC, GIC [General Insurance 
Corporation] and its four subsidiary companies should be changed 
by reducing government share holding to 50 percent. It has also 
suggested that all insurance companies should be equally 
governed by the provisions of the Insurance Act. The committee 
was set up in April last year to examine the existing structure 
of the insurance industry and to suggest changes in light of the 
new economic policy. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

