<F P=100> India </F>
<H3> <TI>   New Delhi, Beijing To Increase Mining Cooperation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0701102594 Delhi All India Radio Network in English 0830 
GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0701102594 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi All India Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] India and China are to increase their cooperation 
in the field of coal mining. India is interested in sharing 
China's experience and technology in mechanized long-wall mining 
in underground mines. Greater emphasis is now being laid on 
underground mines, as over 70 percent of Indian coal is coming 
from open-cast mines at present. Underground mining is 
necessary to increase the production of superior grade coal as 
well as coking coal whose deposits are available at deeper 
levels. Specific areas of collaboration between the two 
countries are expected to be finalized during the visit of a 
high-level delegation led by the coal minister, Mr. Ajit Kumar 
Panja, to China beginning from Sunday [9 January]. 

</TEXT>

