<F P=100> Sudan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government-Rebel Peace Talks To Open in Nairobi </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AB0601191094 Paris AFP in English 1900 GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB0601191094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Nairobi, Jan 6 (AFP) -- Representatives of 
Khartoum's Islamic fundamentalist government were to open 
Kenyan-brokered talks with rebels from mainly Christian and 
animist southern Sudan here Friday [6 January], officials said. 
  Leaders of the two rival factions of the rebel Sudan 
People's 
Liberation Army (SPLA) told the Archbishop of Canterbury, George 
Carey, on Monday that they were committed to peace. 
  John Garang, leader of the mainstream SPLA faction, and Riek 
Machar of the breakaway SPLA United group met the archbishop 
after his controversial trip to famine-stricken rebel-held 
southern Sudan prompted a major diplomatic row between Khartoum 
and London. 
  But despite the rebels' assurances, western diplomats were 
sceptical about the outcome of the talks, hosted by Kenyan 
President Daniel arap Moi as chairman of a six-member regional 
group, the Inter-Governmental Authority on Drought and 
Development. 
  Sudanese Government and rebel delegates held inconclusive 
talks in Nairobi last year after Nigerian-mediated negotiations 
failed to bring peace to famine-ravaged southern Sudan, a vast 
undeveloped region of savannah and swampland twice the size of 
France. 
  After informal consultations on Wednesday and Thursday, the 
talks were to open formally on Friday, the officials said. 
  The SPLA United faction wants a referendum on secession of 
the south from the Arabic-speaking Islamic north, while Garang's 
group would prefer to preserve Sudanese unity. 
  Relief officials here said government warplanes had made 
several bombing raids on the south in the past two weeks amid 
fears that Khartoum is poised to launch a major new offensive. 

</TEXT>

