<F P=100> Tunisia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Security Cooperation Accord Signed With Egypt </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0601105894 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1010 GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0601105894 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tunis, 6 Jan (MENA)--Egypt and Tunisia today signed 
an agreement for security cooperation between the two countries. 
The agreement provides for security coordination; the exchange 
of information, expertise, and visits; and cooperation in the 
fields of combating terrorism, violence, and other crimes. 
Under the agreement, Egypt will benefit from the Tunisian 
experience in combating terrorism. 
  Egyptian Interior Minister Hasan al-Alfi and his Tunisian 
counterpart Abdallah Kallel signed the agreement at the Tunisian 
Interior Ministry. The Egyptian-Tunisian joint security 
committee concluded its meetings, which were held on the 
sidelines of the Arab interior ministers' meeting, last night. 
The new agreement seeks to upgrade the security agreement 
concluded last year and promote bilateral coordination in 
security matters, particularly efforts to combat terrorism, 
violence, and religious extremism. 

</TEXT>

