<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rabin on Peace With Jordan, Lebanon, Syria </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0601182094 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 1605 GMT 6 Jan 
94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0601182094 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin by political </F>
correspondent Gil Litman; at the Allenby Bridge on 6 
January--recorded, broadcast in progress] 
  [Text] [Rabin] ...I will not make prophecies about what 
will happen in 10 days. We should wait 10 days, and find the 
degree of similarity between the Syrian and our interpretation 
of the term full peace, which they have been using. Naturally, 
there will be the question of what it will demand as the price 
for full peace according to our interpretation. 
  [Litman] You were quoted by the French media as saying that 
Israel can sign a peace agreement with Jordan, as far as you are 
concerned, in three weeks. What prevents signing a peace 
contract soon? 
  [Rabin] Jordan prevents this. 
  [Litman] Why? 
  [Rabin] I do not believe that today it is ready to be the 
first of the three Arab countries with which we are negotiating 
to sign a peace agreement with us. We have no problems of 
security nor problems linked to essential territorial aspects 
with Jordan. Today, the issue of the Palestinians, the future of 
the territories, is being discussed with the Palestinians, the 
PLO, and not with Jordan. Therefore, when we speak of peace 
with Jordan, we are referring to the border that existed between 
mandatory Eretz Yisra'el and Jordan. 
  There is another country with which we have no territorial 
problems, but have a security problem -- Lebanon. With it, 
matters are more complex. Also, its freedom of political 
maneuvering is more limited than that of Jordan. I am afraid 
that, apparently, Jordan also feels that it does not have enough 
freedom of political maneuvering to reach a peace accord with us. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

