<F P=100> SYRIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Meets With Jordanian Speaker </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  JN0601143794 Damascus Syrian Arab Republic Radio Network in 
Arabic 1215 GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN0601143794 </F>
<F P=104>  Damascus Syrian Arab Republic Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] People's Assembly Speaker 'Abd-al-Qadir Qaddurah 
received Tahir al-Masri, speaker of the Jordanian House of 
Representatives, at noon today. Shakir Is'id, head of the Arab 
and Foreign Affairs Committee, attended the meeting. 
  Discussions dealt with bilateral parliamentary relations and 
the exchange of visits and delegations between the two 
assemblies in the two fraternal countries. Discussions also 
dealt with issues pertaining to the Arab Parliamentary Union 
[APU], its activities, ways of activating its role, and the next 
APU session. They also discussed the agenda of the next 
Interparliamentary Union's conference and coordination at this 
conference among Arab parliaments. 
  Foreign Minister Faruq al-Shar' received Tahir al-Masri this 
morning. During the meeting, discussions dealt with 
developments in the peace process, Arab coordination, and the 
importance of the Geneva summit between Presidents Hafiz al-Asad 
and Bill Clinton in achieving a just, comprehensive peace in the 
region. 
  The speaker of the Jordanian House of Representatives 
arrived 
in Damascus via the Dar'a border post this morning. He was 
welcomed at the Dar'a border post by Dar'a Governor Dr. Walid 
'Uthman; Shakir Is'id, head of the Arab and Foreign Affairs 
Committee at the People's Assembly; and the Jordanian ambassador 
in Damascus. 
  Tahir al-Masri made a statement to a SANA correspondent in 
Dar'a in which he said that he is happy to visit sisterly Syria 
and meet with Syrian People's Assembly Speaker 'Abd al-Qadir 
Qaddurah and the assembly members. He added that this visit 
opens the way for the exchange of visits between the two 
assemblies in the two sisterly countries. He said that 
discussions during the visit will deal with some bilateral 
issues pertaining to the work of the two assemblies, general 
issues pertaining to the APU, and bilateral issues. Al- Masri 
said the visit is particularly important because it emphasizes 
interaction and communication between Jordan and Syria and 
between the two parliaments in the two sisterly countries. He 
also noted that he is looking forward to fruitful and useful 
meetings in Syria. 

</TEXT>

