<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   PLO, Israeli Delegates Preview Talks in Taba </TI></H3>
<H4>   Sha'th: Agreement Possible in 2 Weeks </H4>
<F P=102> TA0801073994 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 0600 GMT 8 Jan 
94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0801073994 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Speaking on the eve of the resumption of the Taba 
talks, Dr. Nabil Sha'th, the head of the Palestinian delegation, 
estimates that it will be possible to reach and formulate a 
detailed agreement within the two weeks allocated for the 
negotiations. Sha'th said that for all intents and purposes both 
parties have already agreed on most of the issues: the 
timetable for the IDF's [Israel Defense Forces] withdrawal; the 
size of the Palestinian police force; security along the 
borders, on the roads, and inside the territories; and a safe 
passageway between the Gaza Strip and Jericho. 
  In an interview with our correspondent Moti Amir, Nabil 
Sha'th said that there were still disagreements on the issues of 
Jericho and the border crossings, on the security zones around 
the settlements, and also with regard to the division of 
responsibilities between the Palestinian towns and the Jewish 
settlements on matters of mutual concern. 
  As for the crisis in the Cairo talks, Sha'th says the whole 
affair was an unnecessary furor caused by premature 
announcements. Sha'th said that if the crisis had been put off 
for another week, the Palestinian and Israeli teams might have 
signed the agreement that they had already almost completed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

