<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   PLO, Israeli Delegates Preview Talks in Taba </TI></H3>
<H4>   Sha'th on Talks `Without Preconditions' </H4>
<F P=102> NC0901113494 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1036 GMT 9 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0901113494 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 9 Jan (MENA)--Dr. Nabil Sha'th, political 
adviser to Palestinian President Yasir 'Arafat, has emphasized 
that Egypt's support for the Palestinian negotiating delegation 
has been and will remain strong. He noted that President Husni 
Mubarak and Foreign Minister 'Amr Musa are making major efforts 
to support the Palestinian delegation. 
  Sha'th left Cairo today for Taba to attend the Gaza-Jericho 
talks. In a departure statement, he said that the Palestinian 
delegation will negotiate without preconditions, except for its 
commitment to the Declaration of Principles signed with Israel, 
and it will capitalize on the progress made in the talks held 
during the past three months. 
  The Gaza-Jericho Committee will resume its meetings in Taba 
tomorrow, Monday, between the Palestinian side led by Dr. Sha'th 
and the Israeli side led by Assistant Chief of Staff Amnon 
Shahaq. 
  Sha'th said the aim of the talks is to reach an agreement 
with the Israeli side on all contentious issues, which would 
allow the agreement to be implemented in the next three weeks. 
He added: We believe that this period is enough, provided that 
there is goodwill on the Israeli side. If we manage to conclude 
an agreement quickly, there will be a chance for a meeting 
between Palestinian President Yasir 'Arafat and Israeli Prime 
Minister Yitzhaq Rabin to sign and begin implementing the 
agreement. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-52804 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes006yy_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-006 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  10 January 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   PLO, Israeli Delegates Preview Talks in Taba </TI></H3>
<H4>   Sha'th, Palestinians Hold Meeting </H4>
<F P=102> NC0901170294 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1530 GMT 9 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0901170294 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Taba, 9 Jan (MENA)--The Palestinian-Israeli 
committee concerned with implementing the Gaza-Jericho accord 
will begin meeting in Taba tomorrow. The Palestinian side will 
be headed by Dr. Nabil Sha'th, political adviser to Palestinian 
president Yasir 'Arafat. The Israeli delegation will be headed 
by Deputy Chief of Staff General Amnon Shahaq. 
  The security committee and the drafting committee are 
scheduled to meet tomorrow. The civil committee concerned with 
the transfer of the self-rule powers will meet in Taba on 
Tuesday [11 January]. This round of talks is scheduled to 
continue until Friday and will resume next week on Sunday or 
Monday. 
  Dr. Sha'th held a meeting this evening with the Palestinian 
delegation members, who arrived in Taba this afternoon, to 
prepare the working papers that will be submitted to the Israeli 
side. Dr. Sha'th stated that the negotiations will continue for 
three weeks until all the steps relevant to the transfer of 
power to the Palestinians in Gaza and Jericho are prepared. He 
defined these steps as the issue of the crossings, the size of 
the Jericho area, and security along the sea and in the Israeli 
settlements in the Gaza Strip. He noted that the Israeli 
withdrawal is scheduled to be completed before 13 April. He 
pointed out that postponing Israeli withdrawal after this date 
will be considered a violation of the Declaration of Principles. 
  Dr. Sha'th stressed that no agreement will be signed until 
after a timetable has been worked out to release the remaining 
Palestinian detainees in Israeli jails, noting that their number 
now ranges between 9,600 and 9,700. He noted that Israel's 
release of 101 Palestinian detainees recently is merely a 
gesture of good will. He said that the Taba talks will resume 
because the Israeli side gave up its claims of the existence of 
"a Cairo document" for the negotiations, noting that during the 
Cairo talks six working papers were submitted, but nothing in 
them has been settled. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-52805 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes006yy_94005" </HT>


