<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sha'th on Cairo Draft, Syria </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0901122694 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1120 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0901122694 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Taba, 10 Jan (MENA)--Dr. Nabil Sha'th, adviser 
to Palestinian President Yasir 'Arafat, has stated that the 
Palestinian and Israeli delegations came to Taba to draft the 
final agreement during the current round of negotiations, which 
he said is expected to continue for three weeks. [passage 
omitted] 
  Asked about Israel's claims that the so-called Cairo 
document 
is the only basis for negotiations, Dr. Sha'th said that that 
which is agreed upon and signed will be the basis. This was the 
case with the Declaration of Principles, which was initialed in 
Oslo, he said, noting that the Cairo draft was not signed. We 
must not overtake events, he said. 
  He explained that the Cairo document includes some disputed 
issues that must be resolved. But he said there are many points 
of agreement, which makes us hope a final agreement will be 
reached. 
  On a linkage between the Palestinian-Israeli negotiations 
and 
the upcoming summit between Syrian President Hafiz al-Asad and 
U.S. President Bill Clinton, Sha'th stressed that the summit is 
a contributing, not a frustrating, factor for the 
Palestinian-Israeli talks. We want Syria to return to the peace 
process armed with its right to a full Israeli withdrawal from 
the Golan, he said. When this happens, he added, it will 
reflect positively on the peace process and the 
Palestinian-Israeli negotiations. [passage omitted] 
  Sha'th denied that Jordan told the Israelis it rejects a 
Palestinian presence on the crossings between Jericho and the 
Jordanian border. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

