<F P=100> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Musa Comments on Syrian-U.S. Summit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0901073794 Cairo Arab Republic of Egypt Radio Network in 
Arabic 0500 GMT 9 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0901073794 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo Arab Republic of Egypt Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Foreign Minister 'Amr Musa will leave Cairo for 
Damascus today to lead Egypt's delegation to meetings of the 
Damascus Declaration countries' foreign ministers. 
  Musa said the Damascus Declaration foreign ministers will 
discuss the situation in the Middle East in light of 
developments in the peace process and the tense situation in 
other areas of the region. 
  The conferees will also discuss economic cooperation in the 
Middle East, follow up on the declaration's contents, and hold 
consultations on various issues in the region. 
  Commenting on the Syrian-U.S. summit scheduled to be held in 
Geneva in mid-January, Musa said that Egypt believes that this 
summit is especially important because it concerns the 
Syrian-Israeli track, a primary track in the peace process. He 
added that the issue of land for peace will be discussed 
specifically and decisively at this summit, noting that the land 
in question is the Golan Heights, which was occupied in 1967. 
  The summit will also include a discussion on the concept of 
peace, making the meeting an important landmark in the peace 
process. Musa noted that the U.S. role is fundamental because 
the United States is the main sponsor of the peace process, 
which it launched in Madrid. 
  He said that this process is based on several guarantees and 
rules governed by the principle of land for peace, and therefore 
the U.S. role is fundamental. 
  Musa said Egypt attaches special importance to this summit 
and fully supports it. He added that President Husni Mubarak 
discussed this summit during his contacts with the various 
parties involved in the peace process. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

