<F P=100> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mubarak, Ministers Discuss GATT's Impact </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0901154894 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1315 GMT 9 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0901154894 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Cairo, 9 Jan (MENA)--At an expanded meeting with 
a number of ministers today, President Husni Mubarak discussed 
several important economic issues, primarily the GATT agreement 
and its impact on the Egyptian economy. This was revealed in a 
statement by Information Minister Safwat al-Sharif following a 
meeting that lasted more than two hours. The meeting was 
attended by Prime Minister Dr. 'Atif Sidqi; Dr Kamal al-Janzuri, 
deputy prime minister and planning minister; Dr. Yusuf Wali, 
deputy prime minister and agriculture minister; and the social 
affairs minister, the information minister, the minister of 
public business sector, the finance minister, the education 
minister, the local administration minister, minister of state 
for population and family affairs, minister of state for the 
People's Assembly and Consultative Council affairs, the economy 
minister, health minister, minister of state for international 
cooperation; and Dr. Isma'il Hasan, governor of the Central 
Bank; and Dr. Zakariya 'Azmi, director of the President's Office. 
  Al-Sharif noted that President Mubarak heard a report on the 
GATT agreements that have so far been signed by 114 countries 
and represent 90 percent of the volume of international trade. 
He said that the economy minister pointed out that the GATT 
agreement involves three main areas: currencies, financing, and 
trade. Al-Sharif noted that the report touched on Egypt's 
membership in the agreements that were reached before the GATT 
agreement and the positive aspects that bolstered Egypt's 
national economy since these agreements were signed between 1970 
and 1991. The report stressed that the agreements which Egypt 
joined between 1970 and 1991 were reviewed by the cabinet and 
the constitutional establishments. The report explained the 
conflict in interests between the advanced nations and the 
developing countries and the negative impact of the GATT 
agreement on the economies of these countries in the short term 
and the positive aspects that may be gained in the medium and 
long terms. 
  Al-Sharif pointed out that President Mubarak discussed the 
export policy and the impact of the GATT agreement on Egypt's 
export policy and on the system of export shares and the effect 
of the gradual cancellation of the shares system, which the GATT 
agreement notes will be canceled over a 10-year period. The 
report notes the approval in the GATT agreement of Egypt's 
memorandum on protecting Egypt's clothing industry and stopping 
exports of ready-made clothing and textiles in the early stages 
of the implementation of the agreement. President Mubarak also 
discussed the impact of the gradual abrogation of subsidies on 
agricultural commodities over a six-year period and its effect 
on the prices of food and agricultural commodities. President 
Mubarak stressed that the economic policies must be based on 
enhancing the positive aspects and drawing up plans to confront 
the negative effects on the Egyptian economy in accordance with 
future economic policies in the short, medium, and long terms. 
He also called for assessing the effects of canceling subsidies 
on agricultural commodities during these six years by the 
producing and exporting countries and the effects of rising 
prices of the commodities that Egypt imports, such as wheat. He 
called for drawing up economic and financial policies to address 
these factors. 
  Mubarak called for increasing Egyptian exports to the Arab 
and African markets by removing obstacles and facilitating 
procedures for exports, particularly textiles, cotton, 
ready-made clothing, and other commodities. Al-Sharif noted 
that President Mubarak also discussed a report on the 
performance of the public business sector. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

