<H3> <TI>   NDP, Opposition Parties Discuss Dialogue </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0901091194 Cairo MENA in Arabic 0710 GMT 9 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0901091194 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 9 Jan (MENA)--Dr. Yusuf Wali, deputy prime 
minister and secretary general of the National Democratic Party 
[NDP], has announced that the party's bureau staff had met with 
eight opposition party leaders as part of the exchange of views 
on the national dialogue called for by President Husni Mubarak 
in his address to the joint meeting of the People's Assembly and 
Consultative Council. 
  In a speech to the NDP's political club last night, Dr. Wali 
said that the points of agreement with the opposition leaders 
were far greater than those of disagreement. He said the 
dialogue is a good initiative because it has enabled the 
opposition parties to comprehend the NDP's views. It has also 
enabled the party's bureau staff to understand the concepts of 
the opposition party leaders concerning the national dialogue 
issue. 
  Dr. Wali said that he will meet with the leaders of the 
Greens Party and the Democratic Unionist Party by the end of 
this week. Meanwhile, the NDP's bureau staff will meet with the 
officials in charge of AL-AHRAM's Strategic and Political 
Studies Center, which is exploring the various opinions about 
the national dialogue issue. 

</TEXT>

