<F P=100> Western Sahara </F>
<H3> <TI>   Polisario Protests French Minister's Visit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0901144794 Algiers Radio Algiers Network in Arabic 1200 
GMT 9 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0901144794 </F>
<F P=104>  Algiers Radio Algiers Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] So far nothing has permitted the holding of a 
referendum on self-determination in Western Sahara in accordance 
with the UN peace plan. If efforts have failed or have not been 
made in this connection, the town of Layoune in Western Sahara 
has been a focus of attention in recent days. The Saudi 
interior minister is currently in Layoune, which was visited 
recently by his French counterpart. This has aroused the anger 
of the Polisario [Popular Front for the Liberation of Saquia El 
Hamra and Rio de Oro]. Our correspondent Mourad has the details: 
  [Mourad] Polisario yesterday expressed its surprise and 
displeasure at the visit of Charles Pasqua to Layoune two days 
ago. In a communique the Front describes the French interior 
minister's visit to be blatantly at variance with the 
responsibility of France as a permanent member of the UN 
Security Council. Nothing has filtered out about the Pasqua 
visit, which coincided with the presence of Saudi Interior 
Minister Prince Nayif Bin-'Abd-al-'Aziz in Layoune. The senior 
Saudi official has been in Layoune on a private visit since last 
Thursday, according to MAP. 
  The situation in Western Sahara remains generally tense, as 
admitted by special UN representative Yaqub Khan, who has 
further said that he is making efforts to resolve the Saharan 
problem. The special UN representative made this statement 
after meeting President Maaouya Ould Sid Ahmed Taya of 
Mauritania in Nouakchott yesterday. 
  It should be mentioned that the UN peace plan for a 
referendum in Western Sahara is obstructed by a disagreement 
between Morocco and Polisario, the conflicting parties, over the 
number of voters. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

