<F P=100> SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Afghanistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Thousands Flee During Truce; Pakistan Offers Aid </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0801143894 Islamabad PTV Television Network in English 
1400 GMT 8 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0801143894 </F>
<F P=104>  Islamabad PTV Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] In Afghanistan, after seven days of intense 
fighting, the cease-fire agreed between the rival factions is 
holding. Thousands of people are fleeing the capital, Kabul. 
The truce came into effect at 0600 today. The cease-fire 
appeal was made by Pakistan to evacuate diplomats, aid workers, 
and the wounded to safer places. Pakistan had urged the warring 
factions to start negotiations for resolving the present crisis. 
A convoy of about 70 vehicles carrying foreign nationals and 
diplomats has left Kabul. Thursday's bombardment has caused 
extensive damage in the center of the city. Markets and shops 
are ablaze and the streets are littered with debris. 
  Pakistan has offered to use its good offices to end the 
fighting. According to informed sources, Iran, Turkey, Libya, 
and China have asked Pakistan to take the first step and try to 
convince the warring factions for a complete cease-fire. Iran 
and Saudi Arabia will later join these efforts to bring normalcy 
in the war-torn country. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

