<F P=100> SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Afghanistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kabul Truce Said Extended 24 Hours </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0901183094 Tehran IRNA in English 1749 GMT 9 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0901183094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kabul, Jan. 9, IRNA -- The truce in force between 
the warring Afghan factions until 6 a.m. local time Sunday was 
extended to 6 a.m. Monday, it was announced here Sunday. 
  A 24-hour ceasefire was agreed by the warring factions on 
Saturday as a result of appeals by the Iranian Foreign Ministry 
in order to evacuate those injured in six days of deadly 
fighting between the forces of President Borhanoddin Rabbani and 
Abdul-Rashid Dostam. 
  During the past 24 hours residential areas and the district 
around Kabul airport were evacuated. 
  Corpses of innocent people killed in the crossfire between 
the two sides still litter the streets. 
  All government offices and radio and t.v. stations have 
suspended their regular services. Foreign embassies have been 
closed and diplomats are leaving the capital before the 
ceasefire ends. 
  Convoys of foreign diplomats leaving the war-torn city has 
made people worried of the prospect of possible renewed outbreak 
of civil war. 
  IRNA reporter who saw the area said that the ruins and 
debris 
cover a vast area and would take decades to rebuilt. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

