<F P=100> SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Afghanistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kabul Cease-Fire Ends </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0901110294 Hong Kong AFP in English 1018 GMT 9 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> BK0901110294 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kabul, Jan 9 (AFP) -- Fresh fighting erupted in 
Kabul Sunday ending a 30-hour ceasefire. 
  Two people were killed in Microryan district, the scene of 
some of the worst fighting last week, sources said, while others 
reported that fighting also resumed around noon Sunday (0730 
GMT) in Kabul's volatile southeastern districts. 
  The fresh fighting ended an exodus of civilians from the 
capital who had been taking advantage of a 24-hour ceasefire 
which officially expired at 6.00 a.m. but had held for several 
more hours, sources said. 
  It also came as some 65 diplomats, United Nations personnel 
and some foreign nationals reached the northwestern Pakistani 
city of Peshawar from Kabul. 
  The diplomats include Iranians, Libyans, Indians, Turkish, 
Somalians and Palestinians who temporarily closed their missions 
in the Afghan capital. 

</TEXT>

