<F P=100> SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Afghanistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government: Plot To Oust Rabbani Behind Clashes </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0801095594 Islamabad THE NEWS in English 8 Jan 94 p 12 </F>
<F P=103> BK0801095594 </F>
<F P=104>  Islamabad THE NEWS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Islamabad -- The Afghan government is claiming that 
fighting in Kabul, which entered its seventh day on Friday, was 
prompted by a thwarted plot to oust President Borhanoddin 
Rabbani. 
  Government sources claimed that Rabbani's arch rival Prime 
Minister Golboddin Hekmatyar, aided by powerful militia leader 
Gen Rashid Dostam, a close Rabbani ally until last Saturday, and 
the Wahdat militia had planned to move their joint forces into 
the city to capture the Presidential Palace. 
  The government said opposition, who apparently gained an 
edge 
when Dostam switched loyalties and attacked government forces, 
had hoped to replace Rabbani with Sebghatollah Mojaddedi. 
  The government alleged the plot called for elevating Dostam, 
a former communist general, to be defence minister while 
Hekmatyar would remain prime minister. 
  Asked to comment on the government claim, the spokesman for 
Hezb-e Eslami [Islamic Party of Afghanistan], Haji Mangal 
Hussain, said: "We have been openly asking that Rabbani must 
step down. If he does so, Hekmatyar will also resign." 
  Opposition and government sources said fighting, which 
showed 
Thursday night, resumed early Friday with both sides trading 
heavy artillery and rocket fire. 
  However, heavy snow and fog prevented either side from using 
aircraft to stage attacks. 
  Dostam, the only non-governmental commandar to have an air 
force, has been using his planes to bomb government positions in 
and around Kabul. 
  He claimed on Thursday to have gained complete control of 
the 
northern Afghan city of Mazar-e-Sharif. 
  The continued fighting has prompted Pakistan, Iran and the 
UN 
Secretary General's representative in Afghanistan to call for a 
ceasefire and peace. Islamabad had called for a 24 hour 
ceasefire, to begin at 2300 PST [Pakistan Standard Time], to 
permit the wounded, diplomats and UN personnel to be evacuated 
form Kabul. 
  "Pakistan is deeply concerned over the increase in serial 
bombardment posing a great danger to the civilians living in 
Kabul, and has urged all sides to hold political talks", the 
spokesman said. 
  Opposition sources in Peshawar said Rabbani has sent his 
family to Pakistan. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-52839 </DOCNO>
