<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Peres: Position Unchanged Prior to Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0901165194 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 1605 GMT 9 Jan 
94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0901165194 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres stated this 
evening that Israel has not changed its position regarding 
crossing procedures on the Jordan River bridges and the scope of 
the withdrawal in Jericho. Mr. Peres made these remarks on the 
eve of the resumption of the talks in Taba. In its weekly 
session today, the cabinet heard a briefing on the issue. Our 
political correspondent Shlomo Raz reports from the studio: 
  [Raz] [passage omitted] Israel is not prepared to change the 
Cairo understandings, either with regard to the crossing 
arrangements on the bridges or the scope of the withdrawal in 
Jericho. This position was unequivocally reaffirmed by Foreign 
Minister Shim'on Peres. 
  [Begin Peres recording] The Cairo understandings do not 
include 'Arafat's observations, that is as clear as day. As for 
the Cairo understandings, there is the document we issued and 
the observations of Nabil Sha'th -- and they do not differ all 
that much from each other -- and this should be the basis for 
discussion. [end recording] [passage omitted] 
  In anticipation of the meeting between Clinton and al-Asad, 
Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin remarked that if the Syrians link 
peace to the normalization of relations with Israel this would 
be a change. If al-Asad chooses to maintain the current 
vagueness, then nothing will have changed, the prime minister 
said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

