<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Establishment's View of Talks Reported </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0601192894 Jerusalem New Channel 2 Television Network in 
Hebrew 1800 GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0601192894 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem New Channel 2 Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by army affairs correspondent Roni Daniyel] </F>
  [Text] The defense establishment views the discontinuation 
of the peace talks as an indication of a struggle over 
negotiating modalities, and not merely details. For the defense 
establishment, the return to Taba means an understanding with 
the Palestinians that any agreements achieved there would be 
final, and that it will not be necessary to rush every agreement 
to Tunis for Yasir 'Arafat's approval or rejection. 
  The Taba talks will address the Qatif Bloc's area and 
defense 
mechanism; road traffic and how it is to be made secure; and 
that ancient issue of the control in border crossings, including 
that of Rafah. In all the talks, the Cairo understandings and 
agreements will be the starting line, nothing else. 
  If the Taba encounter proves successful both in terms of 
negotiating modalities and the Palestinian delegation's mandate, 
the civilian track will be launched in full scope in the coming 
days. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

