<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ben-Eli'ezer Confirms Map Exists </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0801193894 Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network 
in Hebrew 1900 GMT 8 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0801193894 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network 
in Hebrew 1900 GMT 8 Jan 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report, followed by Gil'ad 'Adin studio </F>
report] 
  [Excerpts] Construction and Housing Minister Binyamin 
Ben-Eli'ezer this evening confirmed that a detailed plan of 
bypass roads in the autonomy territories has been prepared for 
the Defense Ministry. Peace Now announced that if the 
government stops investing in the territories and direct the 
funds to other areas, it would correspond with the government's 
commitments. Our correspondent Gil'ad 'Adin has the details: 
  A grandiose, multiyear plan which would cost up to 2 billion 
new Israeli shekels, was how Construction and Housing Minister 
Binyamin Ben-Eli'ezer this evening defined the autonomy road 
plan. According to him, the plan deals with paving bypass and 
shortcut roads, as well as works on reconstructing and expanding 
strategic roads. The purpose is to attain minimal friction 
between the Jewish and Arab residents of the autonomy area. 
  The details of the plan are being kept very secret. It is 
feared that if the road map is exposed, it would reveal the 
final intentions of the government before the negotiations on 
the second stage of autonomy have started. The Public Works 
Division [PWD] refused to confirm that it had prepared the map 
of the autonomy roads. A contingency plan exists for any 
eventuality, PWD sources told us, and we will be ready to begin 
work as soon as we are given the order by Minister Ben-Eli'ezer. 
[passage omitted] 
  The map was handed over to the Defense Ministry which, 
together with the Prime Minister's Office, is to decide on the 
order of priority for the various projects. If the entire plan 
is approved, it would cost some 2 billion shekel. In 
comparison, this is double the PWD budget for works throughout 
Israel in 1994. 

</TEXT>

