<H3> <TI>   Hizballah on U.S. Delegation in Syria, Lebanon </TI></H3>
<H4>   Al-Khalil Comments </H4>
<F P=102> NC1001061794 Beirut Voice of Lebanon in Arabic 0515 GMT 10 
Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1001061794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beirut Voice of Lebanon </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] A U.S. Congress delegation entrusted to determine 
the fate of six Israeli soldiers missing in Lebanon will arrive 
in Beirut today. 
  According to Hizballah sources, a Hizballah delegation in 
Damascus for the past two days has met Syrian officials but no 
member of the U.S. delegation. 
  The U.S. delegation was expected to arrive in Lebanon 
yesterday afternoon but the visit was postponed until today 
following contacts between the Lebanese Government and the U.S. 
Embassy in Beirut. 
  The delegation is scheduled to meet Prime Minister Rafiq 
al-Hariri and Lebanese areas and villages. It is unlikely that 
Speaker Nabih Birri will receive the U.S. delegation. 
  Sources close to 'Allamah Muhammad Husayn Fadlallah say 
Fadlallah is not interested in the delegation or its mission. 
According to diplomatic sources, Israel has conveyed an offer 
to the delegation saying it is ready to release all the Lebanese 
and Palestinian detainees once Israeli pilot Ron Arad is 
released. 
  Hizballah leaders have said they refuse to meet the U.S. 
delegation face to face but noted that this [communication] may 
take place through friendly powers. 
  Hizballah Political Bureau Chairman Husayn al-Khalil said 
there is no connection between Hizballah Secretary General Hasan 
Nasrallah's current visit to Damascus and the visit conducted by 
the U.S. Congressional delegation. He added that Nasrallah's 
visit was scheduled a week ago for talks with Syrian Vice 
President 'Abd-al- Halim Khaddam. Al-Khalil said: Khaddam did 
not discuss this issue with us and no efforts are being exerted 
in this regard. 
  Al-Khalil said Hizballah officials refuse to meet face to 
face with any U.S. official but he expressed willingness to look 
into the issue through an honest mediator who is not biased 
toward Israel. Al-Khalil said: We cannot give the Americans the 
honor of negotiating with us in this regard. 
  Al-Khalil said any party wishing to play this [mediation] 
role should guarantee the release of all the Lebanese and 
Palestinian detainees captured in Lebanese territory, including 
Shaykh 'Abd-al- Karim 'Ubayd. 

</TEXT>

