<F P=100> India </F>
<H3> <TI>   Jammu, Kashmir Leader Returns, Holds Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0801040994 Delhi Doordarshan Television Network in English 
1615 GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0801040994 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi Doordarshan Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Speaking to reporters at Nandial yesterday, Mr. 
Narasimha Rao said the government is taking all steps necessary 
to combat terrorism in Jammu and Kashmir and that elections will 
be held there once a conducive atmosphere prevails. 
  [Begin Rao recording] I said we will have to deal with 
terrorism, transborder terrorism, exported terrorism, all that 
is going on there. We have to control it, create conditions of 
law and order so that we could proceed toward a democratic 
process, which that particular state has not had for some time. 
[end recording] 
  Political activity has gained momentum in Jammu and Kashmir 
with the former chief minister, Dr. Farooq Abdullah, returning 
to the state after a stay in the United Kingdom. On his arrival 
in Jammu today, Dr. Abdullah held detailed discussions with 
senior party colleagues and reviewed the political situation. 
Talking to newsmen, Dr. Abdullah said that he will reactivate 
the Jammu and Kashmir National Conference in the state. He said 
New Delhi has succeeded in exporting to the international 
community Pakistan's role in aiding and abetting terrorism in 
the state. Dr. Abdullah, however, said a lot still needs to be 
done to fail Pakistan's designs on Kashmir. 

</TEXT>

