<F P=100> IRAQ </F>
<H3> <TI>   Turkmans To Start TV Broadcasts With Turkish Help </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0701161994 Ankara TURKISH DAILY NEWS in English 5 Jan 94 p 
2 </F>

<F P=103> NC0701161994 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara TURKISH DAILY NEWS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Ankara--Turkman TV, which will be broadcast by a 
satellite dish given by the Turkish Radio and Television 
Corporation (TRT), will soon air its first programs, Iraqi 
National Turkman Party (INTP) leader said. 
  INTP Chairman Muzaffer Arslan said Tuesday the system would 
be established around Irbil within 15 days, followed probably by 
Karkuk and Kifri. 
  He said that various arrangements had been made with certain 
private TV channels in order to obtain some program packages. 
"We have also arranged our dish to pick up the broadcasts of 
the International Turkish Channel, Avrasya," Arslan said. He 
added that various groups were "disturbed" by the "activities of 
the Turkmans." 
  When asked who these were, Arslan said, "Our relations with 
the Baghdad government have not been good. Nor are we on good 
terms with its extension in northern Iraq. Moreover, some 
Kurdish groups in northern Iraq are disturbed, because we keep 
our distance from them." 
  Arslan noted that a radio station in Turkish, called Voice 
of 
the Turkmans, had become the most popular in the region. 

<H5>    Training for Teachers </H5>
  INTP has also established two schools in northern Iraq, 
Karaoglan Primary School in Kifri and Dogus Primary School in 
Irbil. 
  "But we are in deep need of teachers and we have held talks 
with the Turkish Ministry of Education to provide schools," he 
said. "We are also appealing to retired teachers here who would 
like to help us." 
  Arslan said 30 to 40 teachers would come to Turkey this 
summer for training. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

