<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Saudi Arabia </F>
<H3> <TI>   France's Balladur, Delegation Pay Official Visit </TI></H3>
<H4>   Balladur News Conference </H4>
<F P=102> LD0901205494 Riyadh Saudi Arabian Television Network in 
Arabic 1800 GMT 9 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0901205494 </F>
<F P=104>  Riyadh Saudi Arabian Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] French Prime Minister Edouard Balladur has 
stressed that the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia constitutes an element 
of stability, equilibrium, and security, and it is regarded as a 
key factor for strengthening stability in the region. He said 
this in a statement opening the news conference he held in 
Riyadh today at the conclusion of his visit to the Kingdom. 
[passage omitted]. The prime minister further said: We have 
agreed on coordination, consultation, and dialogue at all levels 
between state bodies as well as between companies, with a 
periodic exchange of views in order to assess bilateral 
relations and bolster the ties of cooperation in all fields, and 
to give fresh momentum to economic and trade cooperation. 
  The French prime minister mentioned the domains of 
cooperation that had been discussed, such as energy and defense, 
and he said: We have decided to set up a team of experts to 
complete the projects for cooperation which have already been 
discussed, examined, and prepared in detail, and which we want 
to start carrying out. [passage omitted] 
  Naturally, the French prime minister said, we discussed the 
situation in the region and recent events there, and we 
reaffirmed the need for the full implementation of the UN 
resolutions. Concerning the problems of the region at large, he 
said, we both stressed our full support for a just and 
comprehensive solution to the Middle East problem on the basis 
of the Security Council Resolutions 242, 338, and 425. [passage 
omitted]. 
  The prime minister affirmed that his visit was aimed at 
giving a fresh impetus to relations between the two countries, 
and at laying down the principles that will clearly govern these 
relations. He denied that his visit was to conclude precise and 
defined contracts. He told journalists that France and the 
Kingdom had decided to set up a working team to discuss a number 
of projects of cooperation in the two friendly countries, 
complete what has been achieved, and secure progress in these 
matters. [passage omitted]. 
  For his part, and to a question on the problem of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, the French Foreign Minister Alain Juppe, who 
took part in the news conference, pointed out that he had 
discussed this matter with Saudi Foreign Minister Prince Sa'ud 
al-Faysal, and he had the chance to explain the French and 
European diplomacy on this matter. He said: I believe that I 
have given a useful and detailed explanation to Prince Sa'ud 
al-Faysal that permits the strengthening of common understanding 
aimed at a peaceful settlement of this issue. He expressed his 
regret at the appalling deterioration of the situation, and he 
blamed all the parties to the conflict for rejecting the peace 
plans. [passage omitted] 
  On the other hand, with regard to the problem of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina and what he learned in the Kingdom concerning 
the Saudi position in this respect, the French prime minister 
expressed understanding for the concern of Saudi Arabia toward 
this part of the world. He said that at the talks, he had tried 
to explain the French position and that of the European Union 
with a view to breaking the vicious circle surrounding the 
problem. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

